title: Breaking down the entry list for 59th running of Daytona 500
text:
Feb 16, 2017 at 3:51p ET 0Shares 
NASCAR on Thursday released its preliminary entry list for the 59 th annual Daytona 500, which takes place Feb. 26 th at 2 p.m. ET on FOX. A total of 42 drivers are entered for 40 spots in the opening race of the 2017 Monster Energy NASCAR Cup season. 
Here are the 42 drivers entered in this year’s 500. 1. Jamie McMurray 
The 2010 Daytona 500 winner is back for another season in the No. 1 Chip Ganassi Racing Chevrolet. 2. Brad Keselowski 
Maybe the best active restrictor-plate driver to never win the Daytona 500, Keselowski will be aiming to put the No. 2 Team Penske Ford in Victory Lane. 3. Austin Dillon 
Three years ago, Dillon won the Daytona 500 pole in the No. 3 Richard Childress Racing Chevrolet. He’ll be aiming for a race win this time. © , Michael L. Levitt © 2014, Michael L. Levitt 4. Kevin Harvick 
The 2007 Daytona 500 winner and driver of the No. 4 Stewart-Haas Racing Ford will be one of the favorites this time around. 5. Kasey Kahne 
Hard to believe, perhaps, but Kahne and the No. 5 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet never led a lap in all of 2016. Kahne has never won a restrictor-plate race, either. Getty Images Getty Images 6. Trevor Bayne 
Six years ago, Bayne scored one of the biggest upsets in Daytona 500 history. He’ll be going for a second win, this time in the No. 6 Roush Fenway Racing Ford. Getty Images Getty Images 7. Elliott Sadler 
One of six drivers competing for four open spots, Sadler will drive the No. 7 Chevrolet owned by Tommy Baldwin. NASCAR via Getty Images Brian Lawdermilk 10. Danica Patrick 
In her first outing in a Stewart-Haas Racing Ford, Patrick will try to beat her 2013 results, when she won the Daytona 500 pole and finished eighth in the race. 
Getty Images Getty Images 11. Denny Hamlin 
Last year, Hamlin won his first Daytona 500 and this year, he and his Joe Gibbs Racing Toyota will be among the favorites again. © LAT South LAT Photographic LAT South 13. Ty Dillon 
The younger of the Dillon brothers has replaced Casey Mears in the No. 13 Germain Racing Chevrolet. Mark J. Rebilas Mark J. Rebilas-USA TODAY Sports 14. Clint Bowyer 
There’s nobody happier with his new ride than Bowyer, who takes over the No. 14 Stewart-Haas Racing Ford from Tony Stewart. FOXSports.com Chase Wilhelm 15. Michael Waltrip 
A two-time Daytona 500 winner, Waltrip will make his final start in the Premium Motorsports Toyota. Getty Images Matt Sullivan 17. Ricky Stenhouse Jr. 
After several disappointing seasons, Roush Fenway Racing is looking for more speed for Stenhouse and teammate Trevor Bayne. NASCAR NASCAR via Getty Images 18. Kyle Busch 
A Daytona 500 victory is one of the few unchecked resume boxes for the 2015 series champion and Joe Gibbs Racing diver. © Matthew T. Thacker/LAT Photo USA Matthew T. Thacker 19. Daniel Suarez 
After winning the NASCAR XFINITY Series championship last year, Suarez steps up to Cup for Joe Gibbs Racing. 
20. Matt Kenseth 
With two Daytona 500 wins already to his credit and a near-miss last year, Kenseth and his Joe Gibbs Racing Toyota will be tough. Copyright The Associated Press. All rights reserved. AP 21. Ryan Blaney 
A fine restrictor-plate racer, Blaney ought to have a fast Wood Brothers Racing Ford to contend with for a victory. 22. Joey Logano 
Two years ago, Logano gave team owner Roger Penske only his second career Daytona 500 victory. Team Penske should be stout again this year. Getty Images Getty Images 
A rookie with BK Racing, Gase will race on NASCAR’s biggest stage. © Scott R LePage / LAT Photo USA, All Rights Reserved Scott R LePage 24. Chase Elliott 
Last year’s pole-sitter in the No. 24 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet, Elliott will be looking to improve upon his 37 th -place finish in the race. 27. Paul Menard 
Richard Childress Racing usually has good stuff at Daytona, so Menard could figure in the mix. NASCAR LAT Photo USA via NASCAR via Get 31. Ryan Newman 
Although winless since 2013, Newman is a past Daytona 500 winner and Richard Childress Racing has good restrictor-plate cars. © John Harrelson John K Harrelson / NKP 32. Matt DiBenedetto 
For 2017, DiBenedetto moves over to GO FAS Racing. Getty Images Ed Zurga 
Another Earnhardt in the field, Jeffrey will pilot the Circle Sport/TMG Chevrolet. Robert Laberge 34. Landon Cassill 
If he can hook up at the end with Front Row Motorsports teammate David Ragan, Cassill might be a dark horse to watch. Getty Images Getty Images 37. Chris Buescher 
Last year as a rookie, Buescher won a race and made it to NASCAR’s playoffs. This year, he moves to JTG Daugherty Racing. 38. David Ragan 
Both of Ragan’s career race victories have come at restrictor-plate tracks, one each at Daytona and Talladega. NASCAR NASCAR via Getty Images 41. Kurt Busch 
While the Stewart-Haas Racing driver has never won a restrictor-plate race, he usually runs very well at Daytona. 
© John Harrelson © 2015 John Harrelson 42. Kyle Larson 
Last year was a big one for Larson and Chip Ganassi Racing. Can they build on that success this year? Getty Images Jerry Markland 43. Aric Almirola 
In 2014, Almirola won the July Daytona race. For 2017, Richard Petty Motorsports has downsized to a single car. NASCAR via Getty Images Matt Sullivan 47. AJ Allmendinger 
Last year was a disappointment, so Allmendinger and his JTG Daugherty team will try to get off to a better start. NASCAR LAT Photo USA via NASCAR via Get 48. Jimmie Johnson 
The race for an eighth series championship starts in Daytona for Johnson and the No. 48 Hendrick Motorsports squad. Nigel Kinrade/LAT Photo USA 51. Timmy Hill 
If he wants to make the Daytona 500, Hill will have to race his way in in the Rick Ware Racing Chevrolet. 
Brett Moist Photography Brett Moist 55. Reed Sorenson 
Another open driver who will have to race his way in, Sorenson drives f0r Premium Motorsports. NASCAR NASCAR via Getty Images 72. Cole Whitt 
Whitt will drive a Ford for TriStar Motorsports. Getty Images Getty Images 75. Brendan Gaughan 
One of the stars of the NASCAR XFINITY Series, Gaughan will drive a Chevrolet for Beard Motorsports. He’ll have to race his way into the 500. Getty Images Matt Sullivan 77. Erik Jones 
A highly skilled rookie, Jones moves to the new second Furniture Row Racing No. 77 Toyota. 
Furniture Row Racing 78. Martin Truex Jr. 
Last year, Truex and his Furniture Row Racing No. 78 Toyota were beaten to the checkered flag by just 0.010 seconds by Denny Hamlin. Getty Images Getty Images 83. Corey Lajoie 
Another rookie, LaJoie will pilot a second BK Racing Toyota. He will have to race his way in. Rainier Ehrhardt 88. Dale Earnhardt Jr. 
After missing half of the 2016 season, the two-time Daytona 500 winner is back behind the wheel of the No. 88 Hendrick Motorsports Chevrolet. 
NASCAR NASCAR via Getty Images 95. Michael McDowell 
Last year, McDowell was surprisingly good on restrictor-plate tracks, and his Leavine Family Racing Chevrolet ought to be fast this time, too. NASCAR NASCAR via Getty Images 96. DJ Kennington 
One of the drivers who will have to race his way in, Kennington will drive a Toyota for Gaunt Brothers Racing. NASCAR NASCAR via Getty Images
